{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_jacobs_ver01/data/sn84020645/00513684253/1908030501/0820.xml":{"full_text":"MONEY\nTO BUY MINE\nCapitalists\nPrecious Ores.\nMEXICAN LANDS\nOaxaca Mining Company\nis Incorporated.\nIp of R E. Steiner, S3. P. Flower*.\nB. Flowere. Brook* Flower*, and J. J.\nb of Montgomery, yesterday filed\nof Incorporation In tbe office of the\n\u00bbf Probate. The company owns and\nja tq develop extensive mining lands\nBtate'hf Oaxaca. Republic of Mexico,\nmain office of the company will be lo\nin Montgomery.\ntfly outlined, the purpose of the cam\npany Is to mine gold and sliver ore, exist\ning on their property: to buy and eell such\nas they ese fit: to build railways and\nways: to establish plants and commls\nto acquire or osll real estate\u2014in fact\nany privileges that may assist\nthe development of the property.\nThe capital stock of 1*00.000. consuls\nit 1,000 shares, of the par value of *10\neach. The company will begin with a\nPaid In capital stock of *200,000. the re\ng (100,000 of the complete, cspktall\nto be held as treasury stock, and dis\nco the directors see fit.\nThe officers of the company are: Presi\ndent. It. 8 Steiner, Montgomery; Vlce\nPresldent. K. P. Flowers, Montgomery; Sec\nretary, Brooks Floware, Montgomery.\nThe establishment of the company cornea\nas a result of the recent visit of Mr. Flow\ners and Mr. Btetnar to Mexico. While there.\nMr. Stainer states their attention was at\ntracted to the property In question; and\nattar having had aa Investigation made by\nas expert, they purchased It. Mr Steiner\nsay* that tha davslopment of th* property\nacquired le at peasant In activa progress.\nThe incorporation of the Alabama Oaxaca\nCompany la a noteworthy Incident,\nas It marks perhaps, the first\nIS Montgomery s history that a mining\nheaded by local men. ha* been\nIn this city.\nThe scene of the fntnre operations of this\nSimreiiT the Mexican State of Oaxaca\u2014\nShe land of -bright eyes and fantastic coe\nrumee; of imprisoned love elok damsels and\nmandolin tinkling wooer*: of\nnew and extravaganaa\u2014lend*\nUf picturesqueness to th* otherwise\nprosaic, busineee affairs of tha company,\nr The progress of the corporation will be\nwatched with deep Interest by Montgom\nr~\n*f Agriculture\nfarmers everywhere te\nphoephatee and Dey\nFertlUaera. Marks A Gayle. tt\nTiMg Man\nIngham.\nTuscaloosa. March i. (Special)\u2014New*\nhas been received In the city of the\nmarriage of Abe Schweltxer of thl*\ncity and Mlee May Spiro of New York,\nthe wedding occurring In Birmingham,\n2 The ceremony, which was a qutei\none wan performed at the Morris Ho\nted Rabbi Newfleld officiating,\n\"immediately after the cermony th\u00ab\nyoung couple left for Nashville to\nvisit friends of the bridegroom.\nMr*, sen writ *\u00abr is a niece or suae\nRich of this city, and ha* visited haiw\na number of tunes.\nThe young couple will make their\nhome with Mr. Rich on Seventh street.\nei^N-HAUA\nYeans Persona of Tuscaloosa Surpris\ned Their Prlends.\nTuscaloosa. March 4. (Special)\u2014A\nwedding that came as a great surprise\nto the friends of the young people oc\ncurred yesterday evening, when C. C.\nGlass and Miss Louise Bealle were mar\nried at the Baptist Pastorlum. Rev. D.\nO. Dawson officiating.\nThe marriage ocurred. about sly\no'clock and the news was not learned\nuntil the young people had left th*\ncity.\nThe bride has been engaged, as a\ntrained nurse at the Hospital for a\nnumber of years, having graduated lp\nthe training school at the institution.\nShe was born and reared at Foster's\nabout nine miles from this city, and\nIs a daughter of the late Dent Bealle\nof that place. Th* bridegroom was\nalso an employe at th* Hospital for\nseveral years.\nMr. and Mrs Glass left directly af\nter the ceremony for Thomssvllle. Ala.,\nand from there they will go Lasca.\nAla., where they will make their future\nhome.\nPer Ecsusa, Tetter and\nRims-Warns,\nTry Ware\u2019s Tetter Ointment.\nPer sale at all Drag Stores. St.\nWON'T RAISE RATES\n\nDENVER HOTEL MEN ARE PLEDGED\nIlf WRITING.\nPresident of the Heaver Chamber ef\nCommerce Mskra a Public State\nsman\u2014Visitors Will Receive\na Cordial Welcome.\nDenver. Col., March 4.\u2014E. L Schotts.\nPresident of the Chamber of Commerce\nIssued a statement today In which he\nmade clear the fact that Denver hotel\nmen were pledged not to raise rates\nduring the meeting of the Democratic\nNational Convention.\n\u201cThere ha* been nrlnted In many\nnewspapers sn erroneous statement to\nthe effect that the Denver hotel men\npaid a large share of the $100,000 rais\ned to help defray the expenses of the\nNational Democratic Convention and\nthat they Intend to make it back by\nraising ratsa.\u201d said Mr. Bcholt. \u201cAs\na matter of fact, th* contributions of\nthe hotel men were lnslgnlfleant com\npared with what was glvsn by other\nInterests. The hotel men are pledged\nIn writing not to raise their rates be\nyond what Is charged for meals and\nrooms at ordinary times and there will\nbe no just ground for complaint on thf\npart of any one who comes here to at\ntend the National Democratic Conven\ntion. There Is no truth In the asser\ntion that rates will be raised here dur\ning the convention and this statement\nIs made to sst at anv uneasiness\nthat may have been caused by such\nmisleading statements.\u201d\nW. F. R. Mills. Secretary of the\nChamber of Commerce and a prominent\nRepublican, supplemented Mr. Scholtz's\nstatement In a similar version.\n\"I am a Republican.\u201d said Mr. Mills.\n\"but 1 want every one to know that\nnothing will be left un\u00a3sne by the Re\npublican eltlxenp of.BWnver to make all\nwho\u2018come to ttla meeting of the Demo\ncratic National Convention feel at home\nand enjoy their stay here. There will\nbe no extortion and every visitor will\ndepart satisfied with treatment he re\nceives It Is a matter of orlde on the\npart of all citisens of Denver to treat\nevery visitor to this city a little bet\nter than he Is treated In any other elty\nin the country.\u201d\nThe new auditorium will be ready for\noccupancy June IB. An Immense State\nreception and ball, to which all the of\nficers of the various States of the Union\nwill be asked to send representatives,\nwill be held there Just prior to the Dem\nocratic Convention which meets July T.\nKNIGHTS IN MOBILE\nVISITING PARTY IS SHOWN MCCM\nHOSPITALITY.\nEatwtalHl kr Mrnltn nf Lwal Cm.\nHI, KiliWa *f ColuHs sH\nLeave ea iRdal Trala\nfar Blrnlatkaa.\nMobile, March 4.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The\ndelegation of 150 Knights of Columbus\nwhich arrived In the city at alt early\nhour this morning, was royally enter\ntained today and tonight by the leeal\ncouncir who In return was presented\nwith a handsome silver loving cup by\nthe visitors.\nThe visitors were met at the train\nthis morning by a delegation from the\nlocal council which escorted the visi\ntors to mass at the Cathedral. Fol\nlowing this they were taken over the\ncity In automobiles to every oolnt of\nInterest.\nShortly after noon the visitors, with\nmany of the local Knights, gathered\nIn the Cawthon Vineyard where the\nMayor welcomed them to the cltv. as\ndid Matt Mahorner, for theveduncll.\nThis afternoon the visitors were\ntaken to Spring Hill College where the\nstudents gave a one-act play in their\nhonor.\nThey left tonight over the Louisville\nand Nashville in a special grain for\nBirmingham.\nMobile Team Comlag Here.\nMobtl.e March 4.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Mana\nger W. B. Howard, of the local T. M. C.\nA. basket ball team announced tonight\nthat he had completed arrangements\ntoday whereby the local live would\nmeet the Montgomery team In Mont\ngomery on March II. Manager How\nard states that he will go after this\ngame strong and will decide who are\nthe champions of the 8tate by taking\ntwo straights.\nOHIO RANK LOOTED.\nSafe Crackers Seewre Big Cash Sam sad\nSecurities.\nCincinnati, O.. March 4.\u2014Safe crack\ners early today robbed the Mount Grab\nBank, in Mount Orab, O., forty miles\neast of Cincinnati, on the Norfolk and\nWestern Railway of $3,000 |g currency\nand securities and made their escape.\nThe robbers, four or five In number,\nforced an entrance Into the bank by\nforcing a rear window and applied\nnltro glycerine to IM vault. The\nheavy charge of exploetve shattered the\nvaults and partially wrecked the build\ning. The explosion shook the entire\nvlllag*.\nGuests In the Brown Hotel, across the\nstreet from the hank, were awakened.\nThey were too late, however, to stop\nthe robbers, who made good' their es\ncape. In 'the direction of Fayetteville,\nIn the buggy which they had In an\nother part of the city.\nROOSKVKLT CANT ATTEND.\nPresident Will Not Visit Frisco to Wel\ncome Fleet.\nSan Francisco, March 4.\u2014Mayor Tay\nlor received a letter from President\nRoosevelt yesterday saying that neith\ner the President or Secretary Root will\nbe able to make the trip to the Pa\ncific coast to be present on the arrival\nof Admiral Evans\u2019s fleet.\nTire President said that Secretary of\nthe Navy Metcalf, who Is the proper\nofficial to receive the fleet on such an\noccasion, will be present, and will act as\nthe President's representative.\nFISH FOR LENT.\nOver a Million Ponnds on Sale la New\nYork Market.\nNew York. March 4.\u2014In preparation\nfor the Lenten season, there was of\nfered for sale In New York this morn\ning 1,800,000 pounds of flsh, perhaps\nthe largest supply ever In the city at\none time.\nMost of the flsh comes off the ice. but\nbefore the season la over, the fresh flsh\nof the spring will be coming Into the\nmarket in great quantities. Already\nshad Is In the market, but It cornea In\n5.<\u2019V\n\u00abKvnmt\nNOURISHING WHISKEY\nThere if no ohafice for disappointment in ruing our whiskies. Their virtues are uni.\nform_their quality never changes. We have been distillers for forty years\u2014know from\nactual experience how to make whiskey, and how to properly age it.\nTo be benefH*i whiskey must be old. Our whiskies are ripe and mellow with age.\nThey have in slightly charred oak barrels in our own warehouses for years. They are\nmyyyfriitaiy_tonicy, and unsurpassed for up-building run-down systems. These are facts\njour family physician will confirm them.\nThe superior medicinal qualities of our whiskies make them indispensable in the sick\nroom. They are valuable in the treatment of colds, grippe, indigestion, etc.\n\u201cAsk The Revenue Officer\nPRICES\nEXPRESS PREPAID\nRye\nX. X x..*..\nJefferson ...j,.......-......\nCabinet....\nBose\u2019s ATRO....\nJacksonville Club.\nRose\u2019s Purity.i\nRose\u2019s Perfect....\nBose\u2019s Constitution..\nCorn'\nBose\u2019s Mountain Dew....,\nCobb....\nBose\u2019s Blue Ridge..\nBose\u2019s 8weet Mash..\nBose s ATRO\nBose\u2019s Old Georgia..\nBose\u2019s Reserve Stock....\nTennessee Whiskies\nBose\u2019s Tennessee.\nBose\u2019s Crest.,.,..\nGallon\nJug\n2.50\nj!20\n2-Gallon\nJug\n4.75\n4.00\n4.00\n4.50\n5.50\n6.15\n7!75\n7.75\n8.75\n10.75\nFour\nQuarts\n*rso\n3.50\n3.40\n4.25\n4.25\n5.00\n6.00\n\nTwelve\nQuarts\n\n7.00\n9.00\n10.20\n11.50\n11.60\n13.00\n16.00\n$2.60 4.75\n2.70\n3.00\n3.20\n4.00\n2.50\n3.00\n5.15\n5.75\n6 15\n7.75\n4.75\n5.75\n2.50\n3.00\n3.25\n3.40\n'8.50\n4.25\ni 2.50\n3.00\n7.00\n8.00\n9.00\n10.20\n9.50\n11.50\n7.00\n8.50\nExpress Charges Prepaid only to towns reached by Southern Express Co.\nR. M. ROSE CO.\nDistillers\nChattanooga, Tenn. Jacksonvillefl Fla.\nOrder from the nearest point.\nr\u00ab(ri|mttr ears trial the Florida\ncoast.\nLIFE THKBATEilED.\nNew York.. March 4.\u2014Mlaa Grace\nstracban. who has ted the flsht In the\nLegislature for pay for women teach\ners equal to that given men In the same\npositions, has Informed the police of\nBrooklyn where she lives that.she has\nrecently received letters threatening her\nwith death If she does not give up her\nfight for the equal pay bills In the Leg\nislature. i\nAlthough the police are Inclined to\nthink the sending of the letters a Joke,\ndetectives have been put on the case\nand the postoflce authorities have been\nnotified. t\nHONOR ST. ^PATRICK\nANCIENT 0RDEH OF HIBERNIANS TO\nCELEBRATE.\nMontgomery 1Mvision Appoints Com\nmittee te Prepare -Appropriate\nCeremonies For Observance ef\nIreland\u2019s Greatest Day.\nFor a proper celebration of March 17,\nfit. Patrick's Day. Montgomery Division\nNo. 1 ancient order of Hlberlans. last\nnight determined upon the appoint\nment of a committee to prepare a\nprogram of ceremonies, which will\ncomprise SsServIce In St. Peter's Church\nat I o'clock In the morning, and a social\ngathering of the members and friends\nof the order In the Knlghte of Colum\nbus Hall on North Perry Btrdet at\np. m.\nThe mehtlng of the division was held\nlast night in the hall of the1 Knights\nof Columbus and was largely attended.\nPresident Hugh Meehan was In the\nchair. It was determined that no\nparade would be held this year but\nthe other ceremonies usual on thg Day\nwill take place.\nRev. Father Turner of Pensacola,\nselected to deliver the panegyric In St.\nPetir's, la one of the moat eloquent\norators of the South, and hie address\nIs expected to be a masterpiece.\nThe meeting In the evening will be\nenlivened with music and speeches and\nwill be almost entirely a social affair.\nThe committee on arrangements ap\npointed last night consists of T. J.\nKelly. Chairmen: W. H. Kohn, James\nMcIntyre, Hugh Gallagher, Hugh Mee\nhan.\nA PANIC PREVENTION\nTHIS IS DEFINITION OF ALDH&H\nCURRENCY BILL.\nSenator Albert Hopktaa Speaks la Fa\nvor of tho Bill aad Points Oat\nIts Many Good\nFeatures.\nWashington. March 4_Senator Al\nbert Hopkins of Illinois today spoke\nIn favor of the Aldrich currency bill.\n\"This Is not the time.\u201d he said, \"to\nattempt to revolutionise our present\nbanking system. Indeed, it is not the\ntime to discuss ths question as to\nwhether the present banking system of\nths United States oonsists of patchwork\nlegislation as Is contended by some\nSenators or as to whether It embodies\nas good a system. If not better, than\nany that hae heretofore been had or can\nbe devised for the American people.\u201d\nAll. that the Aldrich bill purports to\ndo. he declared. Is to provide means for\na prevention of tho financial panic that\ncommenced in the last days of Octo\nber, 1967\u2014 It throws no obstacle In the\nway of development of State and sav\nings /banks or of the national banks.\nIf this measure Is beneficial to the\nbanks of New York and Chicago, he\nsaid, it la beneficial to every national\nbank that Is in existence today or that\ncan be organised In tha future under\nthe present banking act.\n\"If the New York banks are affect\ned, all banks of the country are In\nvolved In trouble,\u201d he said. There will\nnever be, he contended, another panic\nao long as the banks of New York are\nin a normal condition. 'He was opposed\nto pending amendments for guarantee\ning deposits of national banka\n\"This idea.\" he added, \"that a man\nwho partrwlth his money must have a\nguardian In the Government of the\nUnited States or In the State, as some\nof the Senators have argued, -with the\nState banks to Insure a return on the\ncontract that he makes his depqslt. Is\nrank socialism. It destroys all Individ\nual responsibility in the depositor and\nresponsibility In the bank.\"\nHe pointed out that such legislation\nwould affect adversely State banks,\nsavings banks, private banks and loan\nand trust companies.\n\"There is no more reason.' declared\nMr. Hopkins, \"why a man should be\nguaranteed the return of his funds that\nha placed under contract with a State\nor National bank, than that there la a\nperson should be guaranteed a good\ncrop return who makes investments In\nplanting hts crops, hoping that the\nseason will bring forth a bountiful re\nturn. The man that deposits his money\nIn the bank under contract should him\nself assume whatever hazard there la\nIn getting that money back, precisely\naa the farmer has to assume hazard of\nthe expense and the time and labor\nthat he is put to in planting and sow\ning his crop In the spring, hoping for\nthe return ip midsummer or fall.\n\"Financial .panics are not produced\nby depositors withdrawing their funds\nfrom banks, either State or National.\nThe action of depositors in withdraw\ning their funds from aj>ank Is only one\nof the evidences that a financial panic\nis already on the community or the\ncountry. Financial stringency and In\ndeed, panics, are incident to all com\nmercial countries. They are an Inevit\nable part of the commercial history\nof everv civilized nation. That they\nhave been more frequent In this coun\ntry than others is due to the fact that\nwe have developed more rapidly In pop\nulation, in industries and commerce and\ntrade than any other civilized country.\"\nCONGRESS\nSummary mi Senate.\nWashington, March 4\u2014Currency leg\nislation was the subject of considera\ntion In the Senate today. Senator Hey\nburn opposed the pending bill and de\nclared that It was useless and he would\nnot vote for It.\nSenator Hopkins spoke at length In\nsupport of the bill. Senator Bailey\nstated that he would speak on the cury\nrency bill Monday and Senator Depew\nwill speak on Friday. Senator Aid\nrich announced that he_ hoped to have\na vote on the measure next Wednes\nday. After address had been made\non the bill to Increase the pay of the\narmy the Senate adjourned at 5 p. m.\nNummary of Mouse.\nWashington, March 4.\u2014The postof\nflce appropriation bill techntcally_was\nunder consideration In the House to\nday but the discussion under license of\ngeneral debate took a wage range.\nSpeculation In cotton, finance, the\ntariff and a number of miscellaneous\nmatters In turn occupied the whole\ntime of the session. Mr. 81ms. of Ten\nnessee. spcke In favor of the Burleston\nbill to abolish dealings In cotton fu\ntures; Messrs. Chaney of Indiana, and\nI.lndborg, of Minnesota, talked on the\nfinancial questlou; Mr. Hitchcock, of\nNebraska, pleaded for the placing on\nthe free list of wood pulp and print\npaper. and several others secured the\nfloor for brief periods.\nGeneral debate on the appropriation\nbill will conclude tomorrow at 3\no\u2019clock when it will be read for amend\nment.\nTO FREE SCUDAMORE\nSUPREME COURT GRANTS WRIT OS'\nHABEUS CORPUS.\nRelative* at PtHjUl\nPeaaacala Wartrtn* t*\nHI* Releaa* fwa laaaa*\nPensacola, March I.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The\nfamous George C. Scudamore case, has\nbeen taken to the supreme court.\nScudamore was recently adjudgea\nInsane and committed to the Insane\nasylum. The relatives of the deposed\ncashier. wty> la alleged to have embez\nxled large amounts from the Bang and\nTrust Company, are endeavoring to\nhave custody of him and their attor\nneys today apeared before the supreme\ncourt at Talfahaseee and applied tor a\nwrit of habeas corpus directed to the\nsherlS.\nThis was granted and the hearing\nwas set for the next Wednesday. At\ntorneys for Scudamore will endeavor\nto have the law committing him to the\nasylum declared unconstitutional Inas\nmuch as It does not give a man the\nright to defend himself.\ntab Collide* With Car.\nTwo horses were killed and Alex\nMontgomery, the driver of a cab'***'\nhaps fatally wounded today when a\n,treet car struck the turnout on Pala\ntox street. Two care were passing,\nfind Montgomery did not\nhound car but drove his horses on the\ntrack.\nThere are *ome *kl\u00bb*s aH ann eaH\nO ml*St each are the Daybreak\nIscrs and Add Phoephatee. Right\nrice*. Marks A Gayle. tf.\nA DOUBLE WEDDING.\ndottier and Daaghter .Decease Brldea\nat Same Time.\nChicago. March 4.--A double wedding\nit which mother and daughter were the\nirldes. was the unusual service wnicn\n:hloego gave to the events of y\u00ab*t*^\u2018\nlay. The brides were Mrs. Adel la Mc\n{ey, widow of Henry McKey. and her\nlaughtsr. Miss Gertrude McKey.\nMrs. McKey was married to Mr.\nYielding A. Randel, and Miss McKey\n>ecame the bride of Mr. Edwin A.\nframe, the service taking place at the\ntome pf MrB. McKey. Mrs. Randel haa\n>een 4 resident of Chicago for the last\nhlrty-one year\u00ae. She 1\u00ae a dlatant rel\nitlve of Dr. Charles Parkhurst.\nTO CATABWH SUFFERERS\nGood Advice and Liberal Offer\nFrom a Well Known Mont\ngomery Druggist.\nE. G. Fowler le advising all .who\nsuffer from any of the symptom# of ca\ntarrh, such as offensive breath, dryness\nof the nose, pain across the eyes, stop\npage of Ahe nose, discharges and drop\nping# In the throat, coughing spasms\nand general weakness and debility, \u25a0to\nuse Hyomel. He goes eo far as to offer\nto refund the money to any user of Ry\nomel who Is not perfectly satisfied with\nthe result#\nQuick relief follows the use of the\nHyomeo treatment; the stoppage of ths\nnose Is removed, the dropping ceases,\nthe breath becomes pure and sweet,\nand the catarrhal germs are destroyed\nand their growth prevented.\nGo to E. O. Fowler today and buy. a\ncomplete Hyomel outfit for |1.00 with\nthe understanding that If it doea not\ngive eatlsfactlon, your money will be\nrefunded.\nEconomy\nIn Rubl>er Goods\nMeans baying the better\nkind. A cheap Fountain\nor Hot Water Bottle is ex\npensive at any price.\nWhen you buy any rubber\narticle of the\n\u201cKandeek\u201d\nBrand\nYou take no\" chances.\nWith every \u201cKantlefek\u201d\nFountain Syringe or Hot\nWater Bottle, you receive\na written guarantee of\nTwo Years satisfactory\nservice. Prices are most\nreasonable.\nT\n7\n\u25a0h>n\u00bb IHt-HM\nIndian River\nORANGES\nSpecial this week at 35c\nand 40c the dozen\u2014fresh, In\ndian River Oranges, just re\nceived.\nThese are the good kind,\njuicy and sweet. They are\neveryone tree-ripened and\nshipped to us by fast ex\npress. Place your order\nearly.\nNettles\nGrocery Go.,\n226\u2014PHONES\u2014958.\nJ. L. HALL, W. F. VANDIVER, R. E.\nPresident. Vice-President. CMhier\nB. 8. WILLIAMS, Receiving and Paying Teller.\nAlabama Bank Trust Co.\nMONTGOMERY, ALA.\nA New B